{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":958,"record_hash":"sha256:ef6559cc3133466d2d9a6fc596a975f047a52b7ffa1f7c9cffb74f85e6a743f0","timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:12:40.584Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"previous_status\":{\"completed\":\"Lane C result: **don’t use AWS object storage as the live Git filesystem.** Use local disk for live repos; use S3/R2/Tigris for outputs, backups, and maybe cache archives.\\n\\nMy preferred path:\\n\\n1. **V1 light path:** stateless generator job with local ephemeral disk, fetch metadata, generate projection, write JSON result to object storage.\\n2. **If latency/cost hurts:** add one persistent volume/cache.\\n3. **If AWS:** pick **EC2 + EBS** before ECS/Fargate + EFS. It’s boring, but correct.\\n\\n| Option | Fit | Verdict |\\n|---|---:|---|\\n| **EC2 + EBS** | Best AWS live-cache option | Real block storage, good for Git + SQLite, simplest AWS durable setup. One small VM, one EBS volume, systemd/Docker. |\\n| **ECS/Fargate + ephemeral disk + S3/R2/Tigris outputs** | Good v1 | No durable repo cache, but simple jobs. Fargate gives 20 GiB default, up to 200 GiB ephemeral storage. |\\n| **ECS/Fargate + EFS** | Okay, not light | Works, but VPC/EFS/mount targets/security groups/network FS. Use only if already committed to ECS. |\\n| **Lambda + EFS** | Bad fit | 15 min timeout, 10 GiB `/tmp`, VPC/EFS complexity. Fine for tiny glue, not repo generation. |\\n| **S3/R2/Tigris as live repo FS** | No | Object storage is for blobs, artifacts, backups, projection JSON. Not active Git repos. |\\n| **S3 Files** | Interesting, not v1 | New AWS-only file layer backed by S3/EFS. Maybe possible, but I’d require a Git + SQLite torture test first. |\\n\\nWhy I’m opinionated here: Git relies on lockfiles plus atomic rename semantics ([Git lockfile docs](https://git-scm.com/docs/api-lockfile)). GitMeta uses SQLite, and SQLite WAL explicitly says all processes must be on the same host and WAL does not work over network filesystems ([SQLite WAL docs](https://www.sqlite.org/wal.html)). That makes “shared clever filesystem” the wrong default.\\n\\nSource highlights:\\n\\n- EBS is durable block storage, good for frequently updated data/database-like workloads: [AWS EBS volumes](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/ebs/latest/userguide/ebs-volumes.html)\\n- ECS storage matrix says EBS/EFS/S3 Files are options, but EBS in ECS services is not preserved the way we’d want for a long-lived shared cache: [ECS storage options](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html), [ECS EBS volumes](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)\\n- Fargate ephemeral storage can be 20-200 GiB: [Fargate task storage](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)\\n- Lambda can mount EFS/S3 Files, but timeout is 900s and `/tmp` is max 10 GiB: [Lambda filesystem](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html), [Lambda timeout](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/configuration-timeout.html), [Lambda ephemeral storage](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)\\n- S3 Mountpoint is not full POSIX: no modifying existing files, no symlinks, no file locking: [Mountpoint for S3](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)\\n- S3 Files is more serious and claims file semantics, but it’s AWS-specific and still has limits: [S3 Files](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html), [S3 Files limits](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)\\n- R2/Tigris are good S3-compatible object stores, not live filesystems: [Cloudflare R2](https://developers.cloudflare.com/r2/how-r2-works/), [Tigris pricing/overview](https://www.tigrisdata.com/pricing/)\\n\\nRecommendation: **start with ephemeral local scratch + object-storage result cache.** Add persistent local block storage only when we prove cold generation is too slow. That keeps v1 light without lying to Git.\"}}","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:12:40.584Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}